Create dictionary of V-genes and CDRs¶

  • dictionary contains all possible V-gene - allele combinations and
  • the corresponding cdr1, cdr2 & cdr2.5 sequences
In [2]:
cdrs = tcrgp.create_cdr_dict(alignment='imgt',species=['human'])

Get control data¶

In [3]:
control_file = 'data/human_pairseqs_v1_parsed_seqs_probs_mq20_clones_random_nbrdists.tsv'
store_fields=['va_reps','vb_reps','cdr3a','cdr3b']
controls=[]
with open(control_file, newline='') as tsvfile:
    reader = csv.DictReader(tsvfile,delimiter='\t')
    for row in reader:
        entry = [row[s] for s in store_fields]
        cA = cdrs['human']['A'][entry[0].split(';')[0]]
        cB = cdrs['human']['B'][entry[1].split(';')[0]]
        if '*' not in ''.join(cB)+''.join(cA)+entry[2]+entry[3]:
            controls.append(entry)
            
n_controls = len(controls)

Get feature representation¶

We have used the principal components of a modified BLOSUM62 matrix as features. We obtained best results when using all d=21 components, but is possible to use a smaller d. It is also possible to use also other features, as long as they have the correct form.

In [4]:
subsmat = tcrgp.subsmatFromAA2('HENS920102')
pc_blo = tcrgp.get_pcs(subsmat,d=21)

Read data¶

In [5]:
datafile = 'data/melana.txt'
subjects, cdr3s = np.loadtxt(datafile,dtype=str,delimiter='\t',comments=None,unpack=True,skiprows=1,usecols=[0,5],encoding='latin1')
In [6]:
n_e = len(subjects)
n_s = len(np.unique(subjects))
print(str(n_s)+' subjects, '+str(n_e)+' samples')

6 subjects, 356 samples

Write data files for training¶

Create a separate data file for each epitope. Add epitope-specific TCRs and control TCRs.

In [7]:
epi='melan-a'
with open('training_data/melana.csv','w') as csvfile:
    writer = csv.writer(csvfile, delimiter=',')
    writer.writerow(['epitope','subject','va','vb','cdr3a','cdr3b'])
    for subject, cdr in zip(subjects,cdr3s):
        writer.writerow([epi,subject,'','','',cdr])
    for i in np.random.choice(range(n_controls),n_e).astype(int):
            writer.writerow(['none','control','',controls[i][1],'',controls[i][3]])

Leave-one-subject-out cross-validations¶

Leave-one-subject-out (loso) cross-validations can be used to evaluate the performance of the model.

Train model with human TCR$\beta$s recognizing melan-a¶

  • use only CDR3$\beta$
  • use max. 5000 iterations and learning rate 0.005
In [9]:
_,_,_,_ = tcrgp.loso('training_data/melana.csv','human',epi,pc_blo,cdr_types=[[],['cdr3']],
                     m_iters=5000,lr=0.005,nZ=0,mbs=0,va=None,vb='vb',cdr3a=None,cdr3b='cdr3b',epis='epitope',subs='subject')

human melan-a: 6 subjects, 356 samples

Training, saving and loading models¶

Train the model with desired options¶

  • auc is the AUC score for the training data
  • params contains all necessary informatio for re-building the model
  • Train with 5000 iterations and learning rate 0.005
  • Set the maximum cdr3B length to 23
In [10]:
auc, params = tcrgp.train_classifier('training_data/melana.csv','human',epi,pc_blo,
                                     cdr_types=[[],['cdr3']],m_iters=5000,lr=0.005,nZ=0,mbs=0,l3_max=23,
                                     va=None,vb=None,cdr3a=None,cdr3b='cdr3b',epis='epitope')

Save the model parameters¶

In [11]:
with open('models/models_melana_cdr3b','wb') as f:
    pickle.dump(params,f)

Load the model parameters¶

In [45]:
with open('models/models_melana_cdr3b','rb') as f:
    params = pickle.load(f)

Do predictions for new TCRs¶

  • Now the loaded model can be used for any set of TCRs
  • Here, just for an example, we have done the predictions for the same data
In [46]:
files = ['non_naive_1.csv','non_naive_2.csv','non_naive_3.csv']
seqs_melana = []
preds_melana= []

for file in files:
    seqs, preds = tcrgp.predict('data/'+file,params,[[],['cdr3']],cdr3b='cdr3aa',va=None,vb=None,cdr3a=None)
    seqs_melana.append(seqs)
    preds_melana.append(preds)

Maximum length for test CDR3s is 27, but the maximum length for the trained model is 23.
You need to train a new model with longer sequences to get predictions for all sequences.

Check that all CDR3s have only valid characters¶

remove invalid from training set

I = np.ones((n_e,),dtype=bool)
for i in range(n_e):
    if not all([letter in tcrgp.alphabet for letter in cdr3s[i]]):
        print(str(i)+' '+cdr3s[i])
        I[i] = False

This does not seem too great. Let's try again after removing some strange TCRs

In [32]:
subjects, cdr3s = np.loadtxt(datafile,dtype=str,delimiter='\t',comments=None,unpack=True,skiprows=1,usecols=[0,5],encoding='latin1')
n_e = len(subjects)
n_s = len(np.unique(subjects))
print(str(n_s)+' subjects, '+str(n_e)+' samples')

I = np.ones((n_e,),dtype=bool)
for i in range(n_e):
    if (cdr3s[i][0] is not 'C') or (cdr3s[i][-1] not in 'FW') or (len(cdr3s[i])>23) or not all([letter in tcrgp.alphabet for letter in cdr3s[i]]):
        print(str(i)+' '+cdr3s[i])
        I[i] = False
        
subjects=subjects[I]
cdr3s=cdr3s[I]

n_e = len(subjects)
n_s = len(np.unique(subjects))
print('\n' + str(n_s) + ' subjects, ' + str(n_e) + ' samples')

Write all results to file¶

In [52]:
with open('results/results_non_naive.csv', 'w', newline='') as csvfile:
    writer = csv.writer(csvfile, delimiter=',')   
    writer.writerow(['id','CDR3B','melan-a','meloe-1'])
    for ids,seqs,ps_melana,ps_meloe1 in zip(identifiers,seqs_melana,preds_melana,preds_meloe1):
        for i, seq,p_melana,p_meloe1 in zip(ids,seqs[0],ps_melana,ps_meloe1):
            writer.writerow([i, seq,'{:.4f}'.format(p_melana[0]),'{:.4f}'.format(p_meloe1[0])])
